"""
MKT Context — Luke all 24 chapters
Output: data/commentary/mkt-context/luke.json
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DATA = {
  "1": {
    "1": '<p>Luke-Acts is a two-volume work addressed to Theophilus (a Greek name meaning friend of God or beloved of God), probably a Roman Gentile patron of high standing (the title most excellent / kratiste is used for Roman officials, cf. Acts 23:26, 24:3). The prologue (1:1-4) follows the conventions of Hellenistic historical writing, establishing Luke as a careful researcher who investigated the traditions. The Gospel was written ca. 80-90 CE, after Mark (which Luke uses as a source) but before the Pastorals assume a settled Pauline legacy. Luke-Acts together constitute the longest contribution by a single author to the NT canon.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The opening chapters of Luke (1-2) are saturated with Semitic style (Hebraisms, parallelisms, Greek that translates Hebrew idioms), suggesting Luke is either using Hebrew/Aramaic sources or deliberately writing in a Septuagint style to evoke the OT narrative. Zechariah is introduced as a Levitical priest of the division of Abijah — one of the 24 priestly divisions established by David (1 Chr 24:10). Each division served two one-week periods per year; the incense offering was assigned by lot among the many priests of each division, making it a once-in-a-lifetime honor. The setting of the angel\'s appearance at the altar of incense (the holy place, just outside the holy of holies) is the spatial marker of the narrative\'s sacred beginning.</p>'
  },
  "2": {
    "1": '<p>The census of Caesar Augustus (63 BCE - 14 CE) raises the most discussed historical question in Luke\'s infancy narrative. Luke places the birth during a worldwide census while Quirinius was governing Syria (v.2). The known Quirinius census occurred in 6-7 CE, which conflicts with the Herodian birth-dating (Herod died 4 BCE). Scholars have proposed that an earlier census or registration during an earlier Quirinius governorship may explain the discrepancy; others read prote as before (before Quirinius was governor); others identify a scribal error. Whatever the resolution, Luke\'s historical-anchoring intention is clear: the birth of Jesus is embedded in universal history (Caesar Augustus, the Roman census system), not merely in Jewish sacred time.</p>',
    "41": '<p>The Passover pilgrimage to Jerusalem was required of all Jewish adult males who lived within 15 miles of Jerusalem (m. Hagigah 1:1), though by the first century many diaspora Jews and pious Galileans made the pilgrimage annually. The family caravan from Galilee to Jerusalem took approximately 4-5 days on foot. The social structure of the pilgrimage is key to understanding the story of the lost boy (v.43): extended families and neighbors traveled together in large groups; it was natural to assume a child was with relatives in the caravan before noticing his absence at nightfall. The three-day search (journey back one day, search one day, find on the third day) has been noticed as a resurrection-echo in Luke\'s typological pattern.</p>'
  },
  "3": {
    "1": '<p>Luke\'s sixfold dating of John\'s ministry (v.1-2) is the most precisely anchored historical introduction in the Gospels: the 15th year of Tiberius Caesar (28-29 CE by most reckonings, possibly 26 CE if counted from Tiberius\'s co-regency), with Pilate as Judean prefect (26-36 CE), Herod Antipas as Galilean tetrarch (4 BCE - 39 CE), Philip as Iturean tetrarch (4 BCE - 34 CE), Lysanias as Abilene tetrarch (dates uncertain), and Annas and Caiaphas as high priests (Annas served 6-15 CE; Caiaphas 18-36 CE). Luke\'s secular-historical anchoring reflects his apologetic purpose: Christianity is a public, datable, geographically specific event, not a mystery cult with hidden origins.</p>'
  },
  "4": {
    "16": '<p>The Nazareth synagogue scene is both Luke\'s inauguration narrative and his programmatic Christological-social summary. Synagogue worship in the first century included Torah readings, Prophets readings (<em>haftarah</em>), prayer, and exposition; there was no fixed lectionary for the Prophets readings, allowing Jesus to select Isa 61:1-2. The Jubilee language of Isa 61 (release to captives, year of the Lord\'s favor = the year of Jubilee from Lev 25) would have evoked economic liberation for the impoverished Galilean audience. The crowd\'s initial favorable response (v.22) followed by fury (v.28) when Jesus cites the Gentile precedents (Zarephath, Naaman) is the reception pattern that the whole Gospel will repeat: initial receptivity followed by rejection at the universal-mission implication.</p>'
  },
  "6": {
    "20": '<p>The Sermon on the Plain (6:17-49) is Luke\'s parallel to Matthew\'s Sermon on the Mount — shorter, more economically concrete, and delivered at a level place (v.17) rather than a mountain. The four beatitudes and four woes reflect the Jubilee-reversal theology of Isa 61: the poor are blessed (and the rich are denounced), the hungry are satisfied (and the full are left empty), the mourners are comforted (and those who laugh are warned). Luke\'s social emphasis (actual poverty, actual hunger) alongside Matthew\'s more spiritualized version (poor in spirit, hunger for righteousness) reflects different community contexts: Luke\'s mixed Gentile-Jewish audience includes the economically marginalized; Matthew\'s Jewish-Christian community reads poverty through the anawim tradition.</p>'
  },
  "7": {
    "1": '<p>The healing of the centurion\'s servant (7:1-10) appears in both Luke and Matthew (8:5-13), with Luke adding details that reflect a Gentile patron-client relationship: the centurion sends Jewish elders first (respected intermediaries) and then friends (personal representatives), never approaching Jesus directly. This distance-protocol reflects Mediterranean honor-shame culture: the centurion recognizes that direct approach would obligate Jesus and risk social boundary-violation. His own statement (I am not worthy for you to come under my roof) is a precise formulation of the patron-client inequality. Jesus\'s wonder at his faith (v.9) — the only time in the Synoptics Jesus marvels at faith — singles out the Gentile as the paradigm believer.</p>'
  },
  "10": {
    "25": '<p>The parable of the Good Samaritan (10:25-37) is Luke\'s unique contribution to the NT. The lawyer\'s question (who is my neighbor?) is a genuine Second Temple debate: some interpretations limited neighbor to fellow Jews or even only to Pharisees; others extended it to proselytes. The Samaritan as hero is the most provocative element: Samaritans and Jews had long-standing mutual hostility (John 4:9, Josephus Ant. 18.30 describes violent incidents). The parable does not define who counts as a neighbor (the expected answer) but asks which of the three acted as a neighbor — shifting the question from classification (who is in my neighbor-category?) to disposition (how do I neighbor?). The priest and Levite\'s failure is probably a purity concern: contact with a potentially dead body would render them unclean for temple service.</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>The three parables of Luke 15 (lost sheep, lost coin, lost son) are unique to Luke and form a unified trilogy on the divine initiative in seeking and finding the lost. The social context of v.1-2 is critical: the Pharisees and scribes murmur because Jesus receives (accepts, welcomes, eats with) sinners. Table fellowship was a community boundary marker in first-century Judaism: with whom you ate defined who you included. The parable trilogy is Jesus\'s theological defense of his boundary-transgressing practice: God himself seeks the lost (lost sheep, lost coin) and runs to embrace the returning prodigal — therefore the community formed around this God should reflect the same excess of seeking, welcoming love.</p>'
  },
  "16": {
    "19": '<p>The parable of the Rich Man and Lazarus (16:19-31) is Luke\'s unique social-reversal parable with an afterlife scene. The rich man\'s clothing (purple and fine linen) are the markers of extreme wealth in antiquity (purple dye was extraordinarily expensive; fine linen was the priestly and royal cloth). Lazarus (the only named character in a Jesus parable) is a name meaning God has helped — the divine help he received was absent in life but present in death. The parable concludes with the theological point that Abraham\'s bosom (the Jewish term for the blessed state of the righteous after death) is not available to those who ignore the Law and the Prophets (v.29,31) — reinforcing Luke\'s consistent theme of wealth as a spiritual danger.</p>'
  },
  "19": {
    "1": '<p>Jericho (19:1-10, Zacchaeus) is the last stop before Jerusalem on the road up from the Jordan Valley. Zacchaeus as chief tax collector (architelones) — a title not found elsewhere in the NT — suggests he was the head contractor for the Jericho district, which would have been profitable: Jericho was a wealthy oasis city with balsam groves, a major product of the region. His height problem and the sycamore tree (ficus sycomorus, a low-branching tree common in the Jordan Valley) are vivid geographic details. Zacchaeus\'s offer of fourfold restitution and 50% distribution to the poor exceeds what repentance required: the Mosaic law required 20% addition (Lev 6:5, Num 5:7) and fourfold only for stolen animals (Exod 22:1).</p>'
  },
  "22": {
    "3": '<p>The Last Supper\'s Passover context (22:7-13) is thoroughly Lukan: Luke adds the preparatory detail (Peter and John sent to find the room), the eschatological-earnest longing (I have earnestly desired to eat this Passover with you, v.15), and the unique covenant-cup sequence (some manuscripts give two cups in Luke — a feature that may reflect the four Passover cups). The argument about greatness at the table (vv.24-27, unique to Luke) is placed immediately after the institution, as if the disciples misunderstand the service-Christology just enacted. Luke\'s passion narrative contains significant unique material: the Agony (v.43-44, in some manuscripts), the arrest crowd with clubs and swords, and the healing of the high priest\'s servant\'s ear (v.51).</p>'
  },
  "23": {
    "1": '<p>Luke\'s passion narrative adds several unique elements that serve his apologetic purpose: Pilate\'s triple declaration of Jesus\'s innocence (23:4, 14, 22 — I find no guilt in this man), the Herod Antipas episode (23:7-12, unique to Luke), the mourning daughters of Jerusalem (23:27-31), the repentant criminal (23:39-43), and the Lukan last word (23:46, quoting Ps 31:5). The triple Pilate-innocence formula is Luke\'s most explicit apologetic point: the Roman governor found Jesus not guilty, therefore Roman law and Roman Christians need not regard Jesus as a criminal. The political authorities\' guilt lies in capitulation to Jewish pressure, not in their own judgment.</p>'
  },
  "24": {
    "13": '<p>The Emmaus road appearance (24:13-35) is Luke\'s unique and most extended resurrection narrative. Emmaus has been tentatively identified with modern Motza or Abu Ghosh, approximately 11 km from Jerusalem. The disciples\' unrecognized conversation with the risen Jesus (the recognition-delayed pattern echoes Gen 42:7-8, Joseph unrecognized by his brothers) culminates in the breaking of bread — the Eucharistic gesture that opens their eyes. Luke\'s narrative implies that the Lord\'s Supper is one of the primary contexts for recognition of the risen Christ; the post-Easter community encounters the risen one in the sharing of bread, as in the Upper Room. The Emmaus account grounds the Eucharistic practice of the early church in a resurrection-recognition event.</p>'
  }
}

# Gap-fill ch 21 — all 38 verses
FILL_CH21 = {
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>Jesus observes from across the Court of Women, where the <em>gazophylakion</em> (temple treasury) stood with its thirteen trumpet-shaped collection receptacles (<em>shopharot</em>), each labeled for a specific offering category (wood, incense, sin-offering, freewill-offering, etc.; m. Sheqalim 6:1&#8211;5). The rich (<em>hoi plousioi</em>) putting in their gifts were publicly visible in the Court of Women; the act of giving was not anonymous. The scene is set as a contrast between wealth-display and invisible generosity.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The poor widow&#8217;s two <em>lepta</em> &#8212; the <em>lepton</em> (from <em>leptos</em>, thin/small) was the smallest copper coin in circulation, worth approximately one-eighth of a Roman <em>as</em> or one sixty-fourth of a denarius. Two lepta constituted the minimum permissible temple offering (m. Sheqalim 1:3: one is too little, give the second as well). The widow&#8217;s status is doubly marginal: widows were among the most economically vulnerable in first-century Jewish society (no male support, inheritance limited), and the smallest coin marks the extent of her poverty.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&#8220;This poor widow has put in more than all the others&#8221; &#8212; the reversal of the quantitative-qualitative measure; Jesus applies a different accounting system that the temple&#8217;s visible ledger cannot record. The principle echoes the Lukan beatitudes (6:20: blessed are the poor) and the Magnificat (1:52&#8211;53: the humble lifted, the hungry filled). In the context of ch. 21 as a whole, the widow&#8217;s gift also echoes her situation: she has put in her entire livelihood, and the temple whose system receives her gift will be destroyed within a generation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&#8220;All these people gave their gifts out of their wealth; but she out of her poverty put in all she had to live on&#8221; &#8212; the Greek <em>panta ton bion hon eichen</em> (all the life/livelihood that she had) frames the gift as total self-giving. The contrast is not between large-small but between gift-from-surplus and gift-from-substance. In Second Temple Jewish piety, the ideal of wholehearted giving to God (Deut 6:5: love God with all your heart, soul, and might/resources) finds its expression in the widow&#8217;s two lepta.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Herodian Temple was one of the architectural wonders of the ancient world. Josephus (<em>War</em> 5.207&#8211;226) describes stones measuring up to 45 feet long, 18 feet high, and 12 feet wide, cut from white limestone with gold fittings; the outer walls were covered in white marble and gold that flashed in the sunlight so brightly that visitors could not look directly at it. The &#8220;gifts dedicated to God&#8221; (<em>anath&#275;masin</em>) were votive offerings hung on and around the temple &#8212; gold lampstands, shields, crowns, and other treasures donated by Diaspora Jews and Gentile sympathizers.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&#8220;Not one stone will be left on another; every one of them will be thrown down&#8221; &#8212; the prediction of total destruction, fulfilled in 70 CE when Titus razed the Temple after the Jewish War. Josephus (<em>War</em> 6.250&#8211;266) describes the Temple&#8217;s burning and the systematic dismantling of its stones; the retaining walls of the Temple Mount remain today (the Western Wall). The historical event gives Luke&#8217;s version of the Olivet Discourse (written ca. 80&#8211;90 CE, after 70 CE) its special precision: Luke&#8217;s audience had lived through or knew of the fulfillment.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The disciples&#8217; two questions (when will this happen? what will be the sign?) correspond to two distinguishable events in the discourse: the destruction of Jerusalem (vv.20&#8211;24) and the coming of the Son of Man (vv.25&#8211;28). Luke&#8217;s version of the Olivet Discourse (cf. Mark 13; Matt 24) distinguishes these two events more clearly than Mark does, which is why Luke&#8217;s version is sometimes called the &#8220;historical&#8221; version: the Temple destruction is placed within the historical framework of the Jewish War, while the parousia retains its eschatological open-endedness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&#8220;Many will come in my name, claiming, &#8216;I am he&#8217;&#8221; &#8212; the warning against false messiahs reflects a genuine first-century phenomenon: Josephus records multiple would-be messiahs and prophets in the period 40&#8211;70 CE (Theudas, the Egyptian Prophet, Jonathan the Weaver, etc.; <em>Ant.</em> 20.97&#8211;172). &#8220;The time is near&#8221; (<em>ho kairos ēggiken</em>) echoes the kingdom-announcement of 10:9,11; false prophets would claim the same urgency as genuine proclamation. The &#8220;do not be deceived&#8221; (<em>m&#275; plan&#275;th&#275;te</em>) formula is a standard apocalyptic warning against being misled by false signs.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&#8220;When you hear of wars and uprisings, do not be frightened&#8221; &#8212; the discourse&#8217;s first content is counter-intuitive: the expected signs (wars, rumors of wars) are explicitly <em>not</em> signs of the immediate end. The period 40&#8211;70 CE was filled with wars: the Roman-Parthian conflicts, the various Jewish uprisings, the Year of the Four Emperors (68&#8211;69 CE), and finally the Jewish War (66&#8211;70 CE). These are the &#8220;must happen first&#8221; (<em>dei genesthai pr&#333;ton</em>) events &#8212; necessary precursors but not indicators of the immediate end.</p>",
    "10": "<p>&#8220;Nation will rise against nation, and kingdom against kingdom&#8221; &#8212; the nation-against-nation formula echoes Isa 19:2 (&#8220;I will set Egyptians against Egyptians; brother will fight against brother&#8221;), 2 Chr 15:6, and appears in the apocalyptic scenarios of 4 Ezra 13:31 and 2 Bar. 70:3. In the Jewish apocalyptic tradition this language described the escalating chaos that precedes the divine intervention; the discourse uses it as a marker of the period between the resurrection and the destruction of Jerusalem.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&#8220;Great earthquakes, famines and pestilences, fearful events and great signs from heaven&#8221; &#8212; the standard apocalyptic sign-catalogue; Josephus records all these in his account of the Jewish War (<em>War</em> 6.288&#8211;315: signs in the heavens before the Temple&#8217;s fall, including a comet, a star like a sword over Jerusalem, lights around the altar, a heifer giving birth to a lamb in the Temple, the eastern gate opening of its own accord). First-century readers would have recognized the fulfilment in the events of 66&#8211;70 CE.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&#8220;They will seize you and persecute you&#8212;they will hand you over to synagogues&#8221; &#8212; the synagogue disciplinary procedure (<em>mastigō</em> in Matthew, flogging; here <em>synagōgai</em> as judicial venues) was the primary mechanism of internal Jewish community discipline in the Diaspora; Acts records multiple synagogue hearings (Acts 13:50; 14:5; 17:5&#8211;8; 18:12&#8211;17). &#8220;Put you in prison, and bring you before kings and governors&#8221; &#8212; both synagogue (Jewish) and civil (Roman) judicial venues are named; the pattern will be displayed in Paul&#8217;s missionary career throughout Acts.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&#8220;This will result in your being witnesses to them&#8221; (<em>apo bas&#275;setai hymin eis martyrion</em>) &#8212; the persecution is reframed as an opportunity for witness (<em>martyrion</em>, testimony). The same term will become the technical word for martyrdom (<em>martys</em>, witness/martyr); the early Christian understanding of martyrdom as testimony draws on this saying. Luke&#8217;s apologetic purpose is served: the persecution of the early Christians (Acts 4&#8211;7; 12; 16&#8211;17) is not a sign of the movement&#8217;s failure but of its fulfillment of Jesus&#8217;s prediction.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&#8220;Make up your mind not to worry beforehand how you will defend yourselves&#8221; (<em>prot&#275;leizein apologēth&#275;nai</em>) &#8212; the legal-defense context is specific: when brought before courts, the disciples are not to prepare an <em>apologia</em> (legal defense speech) in advance. This is not a counsel against thoughtful speech but against the anxious preparation that anticipates and fears the worst. The Stoic virtue of apatheia (freedom from anxiety about things outside one&#8217;s control) has a parallel here, but the motivation is trust in divine provision, not philosophical detachment.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&#8220;I will give you words and wisdom that none of your adversaries will be able to resist or contradict&#8221; &#8212; divine speech-provision is a prophetic tradition: Moses received words from God (Exod 4:12), Jeremiah was given words to put in his mouth (Jer 1:9), Isaiah&#8217;s servant was given a &#8220;tongue of the learned&#8221; (Isa 50:4). The promised <em>stoma kai sophia</em> (mouth and wisdom) combines the prophetic (word-reception) and wisdom (discernment in application) traditions. Acts 6:10 fulfills this specifically for Stephen: his opponents &#8220;could not stand up against the wisdom the Spirit gave him.&#8221;</p>",
    "16": "<p>&#8220;You will be betrayed even by parents, brothers and sisters, relatives and friends&#8221; &#8212; the family-division oracle echoes Mic 7:6 (&#8220;a man&#8217;s enemies are the members of his own household&#8221;), quoted in Matt 10:35&#8211;36. In the first-century Mediterranean world, family loyalty was the primary social bond; betrayal by family members represented the complete breakdown of the fundamental social structure. The warning &#8220;they will put some of you to death&#8221; anticipates the martyrdoms of Acts (Stephen, James bar Zebedee, 7:54&#8211;60; 12:2).</p>",
    "17": "<p>&#8220;Everyone will hate you because of me&#8221; (<em>di&#225; to onoma mou</em>, because of my name) &#8212; the universal hatred (<em>misouomenoi</em>) echoes the Beatitudes&#8217; fourth blessing (6:22: blessed when people hate you because of the Son of Man). The &#8220;because of my name&#8221; formula frames the persecution as Christological: it is the name of Jesus, not the disciples&#8217; behavior, that triggers the opposition. John 15:18&#8211;21 develops the same principle: the world hates the disciples because it first hated Jesus.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&#8220;But not a hair of your head will perish&#8221; &#8212; the paradox of v.16&#8211;17 (some put to death, everyone hated) followed by total preservation requires explanation. The preservation is eschatological, not temporal: physical martyrdom may occur (v.16), but ultimate eschatological safety is guaranteed. The hair-counting imagery echoes 12:7 (&#8220;the very hairs of your head are all numbered&#8221;) and 1 Sam 14:45 (Jonathan: &#8220;not a hair of his head will fall to the ground&#8221;). The promise is not exemption from suffering but indestructible ultimate safety.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&#8220;Stand firm, and you will win life&#8221; (<em>en t&#275; hypomon&#275; hym&#333;n kt&#275;sesthe tas psych&#257;s hym&#333;n</em>, by your endurance you will gain your lives/souls) &#8212; the virtue of <em>hypomon&#275;</em> (endurance, patient perseverance under pressure) was a Jewish martyrdom virtue before it became a Christian one: 4 Macc 1:11; 6:9; 7:9 commend endurance under Antiochus&#8217;s persecution as the highest expression of piety. Luke&#8217;s version adds &#8220;gain your lives/souls&#8221; as the promise, completing the paradox of vv.16&#8211;18: lose your life physically, gain it eschatologically.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&#8220;When you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, you will know that its desolation is near&#8221; &#8212; Luke&#8217;s reformulation of Mark 13:14&#8217;s &#8220;abomination of desolation&#8221; (Dan 9:27; 11:31; 12:11) into concrete historical terms. Rather than the enigmatic Danielic symbol, Luke gives the actual historical scenario: Roman armies surrounding Jerusalem, which occurred in 66 CE (initial Roman response) and decisively in 70 CE under Titus. <em>Er&#275;m&#333;sis</em> (desolation) still echoes Dan 9:27 but is now legible as historical event rather than apocalyptic symbol.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&#8220;Let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains&#8221; &#8212; the flight instruction echoes Lot&#8217;s flight from Sodom (Gen 19:17: &#8220;flee to the mountains&#8221;) and the Maccabean resistance fighters&#8217; withdrawal to the mountains (1 Macc 2:28). Eusebius (<em>Eccl. Hist.</em> 3.5.3) records that the Jerusalem Christians did flee to Pella (in Transjordan) before the Roman siege; whether this flight was based on Jesus&#8217;s instruction or Eusebius&#8217;s later construction is debated. &#8220;Let those in the city get out&#8221; &#8212; evacuation rather than defense is commanded.</p>",
    "22": "<p>&#8220;This is the time of punishment in fulfilment of all that has been written&#8221; &#8212; the destruction of Jerusalem is framed as the fulfillment of scriptural warnings, not a geopolitical accident. The OT contains extensive prophetic announcements of judgment on Jerusalem for covenant unfaithfulness: Deut 28:49&#8211;57 (siege and cannibalism as covenant curses); Isa 29:1&#8211;4; Jer 19; Mic 3:12 (Jerusalem plowed like a field); Lam 4:10 (women boiling their children during the siege). Luke presents 70 CE as the fulfillment of the prophetic judgment warnings.</p>",
    "23": "<p>&#8220;How dreadful it will be for pregnant women and nursing mothers&#8221; &#8212; the specific vulnerability of pregnant and nursing women in siege warfare was a standard feature of ancient war-lament poetry (cf. Jer 44:7&#8211;8; Lam 2:11&#8211;12,19&#8211;20; 4:3&#8211;4,10). Josephus (<em>War</em> 5.424&#8211;438; 6.193&#8211;213) provides gruesome details of the conditions inside Jerusalem during Titus&#8217;s siege, including starvation so severe that a woman ate her own infant. &#8220;Great distress in the land and wrath against this people&#8221; &#8212; the &#8220;wrath&#8221; (<em>org&#275;</em>) is the eschatological divine judgment language of the OT prophets (Isa 13:9; Ezek 7:19).</p>",
    "24": "<p>&#8220;They will fall by the sword and will be taken as prisoners to all the nations&#8221; &#8212; Josephus records 1.1 million Jewish deaths and 97,000 prisoners taken in the 70 CE war (<em>War</em> 6.420). &#8220;Jerusalem will be trampled on by the Gentiles until the times of the Gentiles are fulfilled&#8221; (<em>kairoi ethn&#333;n</em>, the times of the Gentiles) &#8212; Luke&#8217;s unique eschatological periodization: Gentile domination of Jerusalem has a God-ordained duration; when fulfilled, the next phase of history begins. The &#8220;trampling&#8221; (<em>patoumen&#275;</em>) echoes Dan 8:13 (the trampling of the sanctuary) and Ps 79:1 (the nations invading and defiling the Temple courts).</p>",
    "25": "<p>&#8220;Signs in the sun, moon and stars&#8221; &#8212; the cosmic-sign language draws on the OT prophetic tradition of the Day of the LORD: Joel 2:30&#8211;31 (&#8220;signs in the sky and on the earth&#8230; the sun will be turned to darkness and the moon to blood before the great and dreadful day of the LORD&#8221;), Isa 13:10 (Babylon: &#8220;the sun will be darkened&#8230; the moon will not give its light&#8221;), Ezek 32:7&#8211;8 (Egypt). These cosmic disruptions are the conventional prophetic idiom for divine judgment on nations; in the Lukan discourse they describe the coming of the Son of Man, the ultimate Day-of-the-LORD event.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&#8220;People will faint from terror, apprehensive of what is coming on the world, for the heavenly bodies will be shaken&#8221; &#8212; the universal scope (&#8220;the world&#8221;, <em>t&#275; oikumen&#275;</em>, the inhabited earth) extends the judgment beyond the specific historical event of Jerusalem&#8217;s destruction; this is the &#8220;great day&#8221; of the LORD whose scope encompasses all history. &#8220;The powers of the heavens will be shaken&#8221; (<em>hai dynameis t&#333;n ouran&#333;n sal&#275;uths&#333;ntai</em>) &#8212; either the heavenly bodies (sun, moon, stars as &#8220;powers&#8221;) or the angelic powers behind them; Isa 34:4 LXX uses the same language for the judgment on Edom.</p>",
    "27": "<p>&#8220;At that time they will see the Son of Man coming in a cloud with power and great glory&#8221; &#8212; Dan 7:13&#8211;14 is the explicit background: the Son of Man comes on the clouds and is presented before the Ancient of Days, receiving authority, glory, and sovereign power. The cloud imagery is the vehicle of divine theophany (Exod 19:16&#8211;19; 24:15&#8211;18; 40:34&#8211;35); the Son of Man&#8217;s coming &#8220;in a cloud&#8221; identifies him as participating in the divine glory-presence. The plural &#8220;they will see&#8221; echoes Zech 12:10 (&#8220;they will look on me, the one they have pierced&#8221;).</p>",
    "28": "<p>&#8220;When these things begin to take place, stand up and lift up your heads, because your redemption is drawing near&#8221; &#8212; the posture of lifting up the head is the counterpart to fainting in terror (v.26): what causes universal terror is the signal of rescue for the disciples. <em>Apolytr&#333;sis</em> (redemption, ransom-release) is the Exodus-redemption vocabulary (LXX Exod 6:6; Deut 7:8) now applied to the eschatological liberation; the coming of the Son of Man is not judgment for those who are watching for it but the arrival of the liberation they have been waiting for.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The fig tree parable &#8212; &#8220;look at the fig tree and all the trees&#8221; (Luke adds &#8220;all the trees&#8221; to Mark&#8217;s &#8220;fig tree&#8221; only, removing the specific symbolic identification of the fig tree with Israel). The botanical observation is about leaf-sprouting as a sign of the approaching season; in the Palestinian agricultural calendar, the fig tree&#8217;s leaf appearance (April/May) was one of the most reliable indicators of the approaching summer harvest (June/July). The parable is a simple analogy from natural observation to eschatological discernment.</p>",
    "30": "<p>&#8220;When they sprout leaves, you can see for yourselves and know that summer is near&#8221; &#8212; the visual evidence (leaf-sprouting) produces certain knowledge (summer is near); the argument form is empirical: you infer the near future from visible present evidence. The same inferential logic is applied to the eschatological signs: just as leaves = summer near, so the signs described in vv.8&#8211;27 = the kingdom near. The Palestinian farmer&#8217;s practical seasonal knowledge becomes the template for eschatological discernment.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&#8220;When you see these things happening, you know that the kingdom of God is near&#8221; &#8212; Luke&#8217;s version substitutes &#8220;the kingdom of God is near&#8221; for Mark&#8217;s &#8220;he is near, at the very gates.&#8221; The kingdom-of-God language returns the discourse to the central proclamation of the entire Gospel (the kingdom announced at 4:43, pursued through the Jerusalem journey, now in its final arrival stage). The signs of vv.8&#8211;27 serve as the leaf-sprouting that signals the kingdom&#8217;s arrival.</p>",
    "32": "<p>&#8220;This generation will certainly not pass away until all these things have happened&#8221; &#8212; the most contested saying of the discourse. &#8220;This generation&#8221; (<em>hē genea haut&#275;</em>) in Luke consistently refers to the contemporary generation that rejects Jesus and the prophets (7:31; 9:41; 11:29&#8211;32,50&#8211;51; 17:25); in context the saying refers to the events of vv.8&#8211;24 (the destruction of Jerusalem, which did occur within a generation). Some interpreters extend &#8220;all these things&#8221; to include the parousia (vv.25&#8211;28), creating the eschatological tension the discourse is designed to sustain.</p>",
    "33": "<p>&#8220;Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away&#8221; &#8212; the permanence of Jesus&#8217;s word exceeds the permanence of the created order. The OT parallel is Isa 40:8 (&#8220;the word of our God stands forever&#8221;) and Ps 119:89 (&#8220;your word, LORD, is eternal; it stands firm in the heavens&#8221;). Applying the same permanence to Jesus&#8217;s words is a Christological claim: his words have the permanence attributed to YHWH&#8217;s word. In the context of a discourse about events that will not fail to occur, this functions as a guarantee of the predictions&#8217; fulfillment.</p>",
    "34": "<p>&#8220;Be careful, or your hearts will be weighed down with carousing, drunkenness and the anxieties of life&#8221; &#8212; the Lukan unique eschatological ethic that closes the discourse. The three dangers (<em>kraipale</em> = carousing/dissipation, <em>methe</em> = drunkenness, <em>merimnais bi&#333;tikais</em> = anxieties of life) form a spectrum from active dissipation to passive worry; both extremes are forms of inattentiveness. The &#8220;day will close on you suddenly like a trap&#8221; (<em>aiphnidios</em>, suddenly; <em>pagis</em>, snare/trap) echoes the trap imagery of Eccl 9:12 and Isa 24:17&#8211;18.</p>",
    "35": "<p>&#8220;For it will come on all those who live on the face of the whole earth&#8221; (<em>ep&#299; pant&#257;s tous kath&#275;menous epi pros&#333;pon pash&#275;s t&#275;s g&#275;s</em>) &#8212; the universal scope of the eschatological event; no one on the inhabited earth will be exempt from its arrival. The phrase &#8220;face of the whole earth&#8221; (<em>pros&#333;pon pash&#275;s t&#275;s g&#275;s</em>) is a Hebraism (Gen 1:29; 11:4,8&#8211;9: &#8220;over the face of the whole earth&#8221;); it implies that the eschatological event has the same scope as the creation itself &#8212; what touches all of creation requires vigilance from all of creation&#8217;s inhabitants.</p>",
    "36": "<p>&#8220;Be always on the watch, and pray that you may be able to escape all that is about to happen, and that you may be able to stand before the Son of Man&#8221; &#8212; the two-part exhortation: watchfulness and prayer produce the ability to escape (or endure) and to stand before the Son of Man in judgment. &#8220;Stand before the Son of Man&#8221; (<em>stath&#275;nai emprosthen tou huiou tou anthr&#333;pou</em>) is the culminating posture: not prostration in fear but standing in accepted presence. The Lukan eschatological ethic is neither passive expectation nor anxious calculation but active prayer-sustained watchfulness.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The Jerusalem temple-teaching pattern &#8212; Jesus teaches daily in the Temple, lodges nightly on the Mount of Olives &#8212; is Luke&#8217;s geographical frame for the final week. The Temple teaching fulfills Mal 3:1&#8211;2 (the Lord coming suddenly to his temple); the Mount of Olives lodging has Zechariah 14:4 resonance (the eschatological battle will begin on the Mount of Olives). The pattern of daily temple presence and nightly withdrawal also reflects the Levitical priests&#8217; schedule: they served in the Temple by day and returned to their homes at night.</p>",
    "38": "<p>&#8220;All the people came early in the morning to hear him at the temple&#8221; (<em>orthrizein pros auton</em>, to come early/at dawn to him) &#8212; the popular acclaim that frames the Jerusalem ministry contrasts with the elite opposition. The early-morning coming recalls the Psalms of Ascent imagery of pilgrims arriving early at the Temple courts for morning prayer and sacrifice (Ps 63:1: &#8220;earnestly I seek you; I thirst for you&#8230; in a dry and parched land&#8221;; Ps 5:3: &#8220;in the morning, LORD, you hear my voice&#8221;). The crowds&#8217; eagerness also anticipates the passion narrative&#8217;s reversal: these same crowds will demand crucifixion at the end of the week.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, DATA)
    merge_comm(existing, FILL_CH21)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'luke', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Luke mkt-context: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
